observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management adopt the procedures laid out in LBC No. 111 particularly the following:

a. Prepare a 5-year business plan, stressing on the importance of directing the LEE operations towards financial self-sufficiency;


c. Five years instituting the necessary changes laid down in the BP, prepare the Financial Self-Sufficiency Evaluation Report which will be the basis in assessing whether the LEE has achieved financial self-sufficiency (or 100% cost recovery) and recommending whether the LEE shall continue to operate and related actions.

We recommended that the Management instruct the:
BAC to:
a.1. stop allowing prospective bidders to submit the same set of eligibility requirements for multiple bids, each bid should have its own updated and project-specific documents;
a.2. require the BAC-TWG to submit a written explanation for the deficiencies noted in the post-qualification;
a.3. remind the BAC-TWG to conduct a thorough verification of submitted statements and documents from contractors by checking the actual availability of key personnel, pledged equipment, and ongoing projects through site inspections or agency coordination; and
a.4 consider blacklisting of bidders who submitted eligibility requirements containing false information;
City Accountant to ensure all necessary documents are attached to DVs before processing payments.

We recommended that the Management instruct the:
CSWDO and DepEd SDO Laoag City Project Implementor to:

a.1. enforce a documented monthly monitoring and reporting mechanism with clear timelines and responsibilities for the submission of required documents;
a.2. institutionalize formal written coordination through official communications instead of relying on verbal instructions to ensure accountability and tracking;
a.3. review the program guidelines thoroughly to simplify the requirements and procedures; and
a.4. implement a regular monitoring and evaluation system to track the progress of the program. Quarterly reports should be submitted to ensure that the funds are being used effectively, and corrective actions should be taken immediately if delays or issues are identified;
City Accountant and City Budget Officer ensure the completeness of supporting documents before recording the obligation in their respective books;
City Treasurer expedite the processing and encashment of checks to ensure timely disbursement of funds. A more efficient system for approving and releasing funds should be implemented to avoid delays and ensure that beneficiaries receive the necessary financial assistance on time; and
GAD Focal Person closely monitor the implementation of the SAFER LARDOS Program to ensure compliance with all requirements and timelines. Regular coordination with both the CSWDO and DepEd should be established to guarantee the timely submission of documentation, proper fund utilization, and efficient distribution of financial assistance to beneficiaries.

We recommended that Management:

Prepare the GPB and GAD AR in strict compliance with the PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01;


Maximize the utilization of the GAD fund to attain its intended purpose and identify appropriate PPAs to address priority gender issues that are included in the GPB;

Require the GFPS to regularly monitor if the GAD Budget is being spent on what is intended for and check on the actual cost of implementing the GAD activities; and

Perform gender analysis using existing tools, such as the HGDG, to aid gender mainstreaming and to ensure that the different concerns of women and men are addressed equally and equitably in their PPAs.

We recommended that Management strictly adhere to the prescribed policies and procedures in the effective control and accounting of supplies and materials and direct the:

a. OIC- City Accountant to maintain the perpetual inventory system and prepare supplies ledger card per inventory item using the moving average method costing;


b. City GSO to maintain supplies and material stock card per stock number and prepare a monthly SSMI and submit the same to the OIC- City Accountant for updating of its inventory records and preparation of JEV to record the expenses as they occur;



d. City GSO and Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to strictly follow the APP so as not to hinder the delivery of basic services to its constituents and effective management of funds of the City Government.

We recommended that Management strictly adhere to the prescribed policies and procedures in the effective control and accounting of supplies and materials and direct the:

a.	OIC- City Accountant to maintain the perpetual inventory system and prepare supplies ledger card per inventory item using the moving average method costing;

b.	City GSO to maintain supplies and material stock card per stock number and prepare a monthly SSMI and submit the same to the OIC- City Accountant for updating of its inventory records and preparation of JEV to record the expenses as they occur;

c.	City GSO to conduct actual physical count of inventories and report thereon; and

d.	City GSO and Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to strictly follow the APP so as not to hinder the delivery of basic services to its constituents and effective management of funds of the City Government.

We recommended that Management take the following actions:

a..	Allocate at least 5% of the total annual budget for the implementation of GAD-related activities as required under Section 36 (a) of RA No. 9710 or the Magna Carta of Women;


b..	Strictly comply with Section 36 of the MCW and PCW-DILG DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01 to ensure that the PPAs are aligned with GAD-related undertakings so that the intended beneficiaries are assured of the services, protection, and other assistance that may be provided;

c..	Maximize the utilization of GAD funds, ensure that GAD PPAs are implemented as planned, and see to it that proper charging and/or attribution is done to reflect the LGU’s attainment of GAD objectives; and


d..	Prepare the required reports to enable the LGU and regulatory bodies to assess its gender mainstreaming status and ensure full functionality of the GAD M&E Team.

We recommended that Management adopt the procedures laid out in LBC No. 111 particularly the following:

a.	Prepare a 5-year business plan, stressing on the importance of directing the LEE operations towards financial self-sufficiency;



c.	Five years instituting the necessary changes laid down in the BP, prepare the Financial Self-Sufficiency Evaluation Report which will be the basis in assessing whether the LEE has achieved financial self-sufficiency (or 100% cost recovery) and recommending whether the LEE shall continue to operate and related actions.

We recommended that Management:
prepare the GPB and GAD AR in strict compliance with the PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01;
maximize the utilization of the GAD fund to attain its intended purpose and identify appropriate PPAs to address priority gender issues that are included in the GPB;
require the GFPS to regularly monitor if the GAD Budget is being spent on what it was intended for and check on the actual cost of implementing the GAD activities; and
perform gender analysis using existing tools, such as the HGDG, to aid gender mainstreaming and to ensure that the different concerns of women and men are addressed equally and equitably in their PPAs.

We recommended that Management instruct the:
a. Head of the end-user unit to coordinate with the CGSO to require the supplier to rectify its non-compliance to the Bid Proposal by replacing the installed strobe light with Whelen strobe lights and deliver the accessories that were omitted as provided in the Technical Specifications;
b. City Accountant to determine and collect the appropriate liquidated damages incurred by the supplier due to delay and non-delivery of the remaining tools/accessories.

We recommended that Management:
ensure that the local chief executive has prior authority from the SP before she enters into a contract whose fund is to be charged to lump-sum appropriations;
consider non-payment of contracts entered into by the local chief executive amounting to P12,408,394.70 for being irregular and illegal and facilitate return of the amount already paid amounting to ₱186,250.00;
adhere strictly to Section 22 (c) of R.A. No. 7160 and other pertinent laws, rules and regulations; and
discontinue treating Aid to Barangays covered by lump-sum appropriations as continuing appropriation unless and until the appropriation ordinance has identify the specific projects and cost of the projects funded.

We recommended that the City Government:

a)	Refrain from transacting business with GLEDCO, as provided for in AOM 2017-012 dated April 21, 2017, pending the response to the query of management, letter dated August 14, 2017 of City Mayor Chevylle V. Fariñas, requesting for legal basis why the City Government of Laoag, Ilocos Norte cannot enter into a contract with the Government of Laoag Employees Development Cooperative (GLEDCO) from COA Regional Office No. 1, San Fernando City, La Union.  However, the proper evaluation of the issues raised by management is dependent on the submission of certified true copy of pertinent documents as contained in the letter of COA Regional Office No. 1 dated November 22, 2017 to management, to wit:

	GLEDCO Articles of Incorporation and any amendments thereto;
	GLEDCO By-laws and any amendments thereto;
	GLEDCO General Information Sheet for 2016;
	List of GLEDCO officers and members for 2016;
	GLEDCO plantilla for 2016;
	Joint Venture Agreements between the City government of Laoag and GLEDCO covering the operations of the latter at the Laoag City General Hospital;
	Necessary documents for the consignment of medicines and medical supplies as well as the fuel supply arrangement for which the BAC had participation;

Memorandum CVF-II-2017 No. 237, dated May 24, 2017; and
City Resolution No. 2002-007, series of 2002.

b)	Submit the bidding documents for the Supplemental Feeding Program, dietary and laundry services, consignment of medicine and medical supplies with GLEDCO and Fuel Supply Arrangement;

c)	Require the accounting personnel to quit from their functions with GLEDCO so as not to impair government function and avoid financial loss on the part of the government;  

d)	Submit properly and correctly accomplished drivers’ trip tickets and Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption; act on the immediate repair or replacement of nonfunctioning odometers; and let all city vehicles be plated red;

e)	Adhere to EO 821 and to the Drug Price Reference Index prescribed by DOH in order to deliver affordable and effective medicine to the public;

f)	Strictly adhere to RA 9184 in the procurement of services as preferential right cannot be invoked when there is conflict of interest; and

g)	Bill the GLEDCO for the water and electricity consumption.

